EPODE IV.

In this epode the poet inveighs vehemently against some ger- son, who, from the condition of a slave, had become a mi ary tribune, and was making an offensive display of his wealth and dignity, to the annoyance of the more reputable part of the com- munity. It is commonly supposed to be addressed to Menas, a freedman of Cneus Pompey, and in most manuscripts it is inscrib- ed to him.
